AGI - "There are no unresolvable problems between Turkey and Greece, the key to ending the differences between us is just dialogue." These are the words used by Turkish President Recep Tayip Erdogan on the edge of the historic visit of Greek prime minister Kyriakos Mitsotakis, > welcomed yesterday in the capital Ankara. A meeting defined by both political leaders "positive and constructive". Mitsotakis echoed the Turkish President, thanking him for the welcome and for the opening and hoped for a rapid improvement of relations with the shady Turkish neighbor. A rapprochement that, according to Erdogan, must be based on a "dialogue between neighbors marked by cordiality and international law" and which leads to a continuous exchange of political visions, the constitution of an agenda and the gradual growth of mutual trust between the parties. A line that, according to Mitsotakis, has already produced positive results that hopefully pave the way for further progress. Monday was the fourth high-level meeting between representatives of the two countries, a certainly positive development, in light of the strong tensions that had characterized the Aegean Sea in recent years.
&nbsp;
One of the main topics covered is illegal immigration management. The border between the two countries represents for many immigrants the door for the European Union. In this regard, Mitsotakis expressed Greece's intention to press on Brussels to ensure more economic support in Ankara to manage irregular flows. The Greek Prime Minister also provided for cooperation in the fight against terrorism. A key theme for Ankara, which has been accusing Greece for years to offer a safe port to the 2016 > escaping goals and figures related to terrorism of Kurdish separatist matrix.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Another spiny theme remains that of the Turkish minority living in Greece,» 150 thousand people living in the Thrace region, who became one of the poorest in the country over the years. To raise tension the closure of Turkish schools and mosques, decided over the years by the Greek government, which prevented the election of local representatives. More than a divisive element Erdogan expressed the hope that "the atmosphere changes" and that these communities become "a bridge that approaches our two countries", more than a divisive element. A vision shared by Mitsotakis himself. The multi-year Cyprus issue remains one of the unresolved nodes. Erdogan has emphasized that to put an end to the uncertainty that vige since 1974 would lead to the resolution of problems that have plagued the entire area for years.
&nbsp;
Not only tension, but also polemics concerning the recognition by the international community of the Turkish Republic of Cyprus Nord> and the dispute concerning the sovereignty over 40% of water and the rights to the exploitation of gas deposits in the area. Ankara does not recognize the Greek Republic of Cyprus and maintains on the island a contingent of 35 thousand men. A situation that blocks the path towards the European Union of Turkey and requires Erdogan to relaunch the negotiations that were held in Switzerland in 2017, in which Ankara was in vain acted as a guarantor. According to the Turkish President the resolution of the Cyprus question, the agreements signed during the visit to the Greek capital Athens last December and the dialogue undertaken and carried out yesterday must pave the way for a reconciliation on which, at the moment, the delimitation of the sea borders is so much weighed.
&nbsp;
A theme not directly mentioned at the meeting: Erdogan has recently declared that he cannot completely exclude the appeal at the International Court of Justice, but has opened a dialogue that leads to an understanding on this thorny issue. "We must proceed according to a holistic approach. You don't have to give priority to one subject on another because they leave unfinished issues," said the Turkish leader. The recent decision of the Greek Government to abolish visas for Turkish citizens wishing to travel to the Greek islands is approaching the two neighbours. A decision that Erdogan hopes to pave the way for visa liberalization throughout the Schengen area.&nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;

